  "prompt": "Clean Master, the Android app, deleted some of my important pictures when I tapped the \"clean the junk\" option. What are some methods to retrieve the pictures?",
  "response": "I'm sorry to hear that you lost important pictures. Here are some methods you can try to retrieve them:\n\n1. **Check Google Photos**:\n   - If you have Google Photos installed and syncing enabled, open the app and check if your pictures are backed up there.\n   - Go to the \"Trash\" section within Google Photos (if you\u2019ve deleted them recently). You may be able to restore them if they are still in the trash.\n\n2. **File Recovery Apps**:\n   - Consider using file recovery apps specific to Android, such as DiskDigger or EaseUS MobiSaver. These apps can scan your device for deleted files and may help you recover lost images.\n   - Note that recovery chances are higher if you act quickly before the deleted files are overwritten with new data.\n\n3. **Connect to a PC**:\n   - Connect your Android device to a computer via USB. Check if you can view the internal storage or SD card contents for any recoverable files.\n   - Use specialized recovery software on your computer (e.g., Recuva, Dr.Fone) to scan your device for deleted images.\n\n4. **SD Card Recovery**:\n   - If your photos were stored on an SD card, you can use SD card recovery software like Recuva or PhotoRec on your computer to attempt recovery.\n   - Remove the SD card from your device and connect it to a computer using an SD card reader for better recovery chances.\n\n5. **Check Other Backup Services**:\n   - If you use other backup services like Dropbox, OneDrive, or Samsung Cloud, check their respective apps or websites for any backups of your images.\n\n6. **Professional Data Recovery Services**:\n   - If the files are extremely important and the above methods don't work, consider contacting a professional data recovery service. This can be more expensive but may yield results.\n\n7. **Prevention for Future**:\n   - To prevent future data loss, consider regularly backing up your photos to cloud services or external storage.\n\nRemember, if you try data recovery methods, avoid using the device extensively until you attempt recovery, as using the device can overwrite the space where the deleted files were stored, making recovery more difficult.",
